Lesson 7 Introduction

ANTH 102-W1

In the previous lesson, you explored the early origins of agriculture and social complexity, but the discussion was fairly limited to the region of the Near East (Fertile Crescent, particularly the Levant)—specifically with the Natufian culture and later Neolithic cultures—and, to a lesser degree, southeastern Europe (i.e., LBK culture). In this lesson, we will broaden our scope to consider domestication of plants and animals and developments in social complexity in other regions of the world, particularly in North and South America (including what is often termed Mesoamerica), Africa, China, and some parts of Australasia.

If you did not get this from the previous lesson, here is one important take-away: the processes of plant and animal domestication did not follow the same trajectory in all places and times. For example, in much of Africa (like Egypt’s Nabta Playa in the map below), archaeological data suggest that some animal species may have been domesticated before any plant species were and that some of these human groups traveled with their animal herds—a subsistence strategy called pastoralism.



Some archaeologists have argued that Nabta Playa holds evidence for the earliest domestication (cattle) in Africa, though this is still debated. Another interesting fact about this site is its megalithic structures and their potential astronomical, symbolic importance.



Also, evidence from other regions of the world, like the Andean region of South America, show that large, sedentary villages and intensive agricultural practices did not necessarily always occur together.

While some of the information covered in this lesson may be a review of previous concepts, we will be looking at some new information, too. In particular, we will consider some of the “mound-building” cultures of ancient North America, like the Adena and Hopewell cultures.

One thing that this lesson will do is further illustrate that archaeological evidence gathered since the mid-1900’s does not support V. Gordon Childe’s concept of the Neolithic “Revolution.” This is not to discredit Childe; he was working within the theoretical frameworks and data available at that time. As with other sciences, though, our models must change to better explain the observed data, or at least be subjected to scrutiny, in light of new evidence.

Objectives

By the end of this lesson, you should understand the following:

  • The archaeological record of the domestication of maize, beans, and squash in Mesoamerica.

  • The impact of the adoption of maize agriculture on the Archaic societies of the southwestern United States and northern Mexico.

  • The complex interaction between domestication of local plants species and the adoption of maize in eastern North America.

  • The context of the mound construction of the Adena and Hopewell cultures.

  • The role of pastoralism and the timing for the introduction of pottery in Africa.

  • The nature and significance of the archaeological site at Kuk Swamp, New Guinea.

  • The relationship between the origin of village life and plant/animal domestication in the Andes.

  • The evidence from the two centers of plant/animal domestication in China.
